iTypically, Docker images are created by running specified commands		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istep-by-step within an existing image. This process poses no issues		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifor most users on x86 architecture computers, as the architectures are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompatible. Images built on one machine can usually run directly on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iothers, unless the programs within the image use newer instruction		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isets like AVX.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, there are ARM-based hosts that can run Docker and execute		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ispecially compiled ARM architecture images. These include Raspberry Pi		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iseries and similar boards like Cubieboard, Orange Pi, Asus Tinker		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBoard, etc. Additionally, hosting providers like Scaleway offer		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iARM-based dedicated servers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince ARM architecture systems cannot run on x86 computers, you can't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly generate ARM architecture images via Dockerfile on x86		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imachines. The common solution is to use an ARM host for `docker build` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut when I created a Docker image for nginx on my Raspberry Pi, I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifound this approach suboptimal. With only 1GB RAM on the Pi, enabling		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imulti-threaded compilation ( `make -j4` or `make -j2` ) causes memory		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexhaustion and kills gcc; while single-threaded compilation ( `make` )		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itakes excessively long (several hours).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter research, an alternative solution emerged: simulating an ARM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienvironment on x86 architecture through "virtualization." Although x86		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iemulation of ARM lacks hardware acceleration (VT-x, AMD-V, etc.) and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis inefficient, the overall performance still surpasses native		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompilation on Raspberry Pi due to the high performance of x86 CPUs.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## qemu-user-static		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first step is to emulate an ARM environment. While we could run a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifull ARM Linux VM using QEMU and perform Docker builds inside it, this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iintroduces challenges: managing an additional Docker instance,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinflexible resource allocation between host and VM, and difficulty		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iautomating scripts for CI/CD integration.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iA superior solution is qemu-user-static, a userspace implementation of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iQEMU. It dynamically translates ARM/MIPS instructions to x86, allowing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iARM Linux programs to run directly on amd64 systems. This creates a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1:1 mapping between ARM processes and host system processes, enabling		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iflexible resource allocation and script automation.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOne caveat: When an ARM process spawns a child process,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iqemu-user-static doesn't automatically handle it. If the new process		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis ARM-based, the Linux kernel can't execute it. This requires		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienabling Linux's binfmt feature, which automatically invokes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iqemu-user-static when detecting ARM/MIPS binaries. Once enabled and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iregistered, running ARM programs becomes indistinguishable from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irunning native x86 programs.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
